Invent your own type of matching similar to 1 and 2 (or look one up on the internet), which has a different way to pick the matches in X = 0.  Clearly explain the approach you invented or found.
- One matching methodology we can utilize is called Coarsened Exact Matching (CEM). To apply this methodology to our dataset, we first perform "coarsening" by binning the continuous Z values into ranges. Since our Z values fall between 0 and 1, we can try a bin size of 0.01 to start. The first bins would be "0-0.01", "0.01-0.02", "0.02-0.03", etc. Once all Z values are binned, we do exact matching similar to Approach A based on the binned Z values. Next, we apply "pruning"; any bins that do not have a row from X=0 and X=1 are discarded entirely as unmatched bins.

