1. The Coding Quiz gives two options for instrumental variables.  For the second item (dividing the range of W into multiple ranges), explain how you did it, show your code, and discuss any issues you encountered.
- The below code shows my code for dividing the range of W into multiple ranges and calculating the effect. First, I had to split the dataframe into ranges of W. I initially tried `pd.cut` to do this, but I had an issue with the final effect calculation where it over estimated what I got in the first problem. I think this was because `pd.cut` does not split W into equal groups. So, when we take the mean later on to find the effect, it equally weights each group of W, even when some groups do not have many rows in them. Using `pd.qcut` I was able to resolve that issue. Once we have ranges of W created, I iterate over each group and calculate the effect using the formula provided in the problem statement (Find average y and x given a Z value and take the ratio). Finally, I append the effect for the W range to a list. Once all the ranges have been iterated over I calculate the mean effect of all W ranges.

```
# Note I tried pd.cut initially but the resulting effect was wrong. I think it is due to qcut makes equally sized ranges. 
# When we calculate the effect by taking mean there could have been an issue with small ranges having the same effect as large ranges on the result
# I picked q as 200 pretty arbitrarily based on the histogram by looking at different bin counts
df["W_range"] = pd.qcut(df["W"], q=200, labels=False) # No labels so that it doesn't becomne a tuple in the df. When we group by it goes by value so no label is needed

ratio_effects = []

for _, w_range_group in df.groupby("W_range"):
    w_range_z1 = w_range_group[w_range_group["Z"] == 1]
    w_range_z0 = w_range_group[w_range_group["Z"] == 0]

    # Find the average Y value for Z=1 and Z=0 for a narrow range of W.
    mean_y_z1 = w_range_z1["Y"].mean()
    mean_y_z0 = w_range_z0["Y"].mean()

    # Find the average X value for Z=1 and Z=0 for the same narrow range of W.
    mean_x_z1 = w_range_z1["X"].mean()
    mean_x_z0 = w_range_z0["X"].mean()

    # Take ratio to find the effect
    ratio_effects.append(
        (mean_y_z1 - mean_y_z0) / (mean_x_z1 - mean_x_z0)
    )

# Average this over all the ranges of W.
mean_ratio_effect = np.mean(ratio_effects)
mean_ratio_effect
```

